Class -- tEpilogue: New Directions for Duoethnography in ELT -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book sets out duoethnography as a method of research, reflective practice and as a pedagogical approach in English Language Teaching (ELT). The book provides an introduction to the history of duoethnography and lays out its theoretical foundations. The chapters then address duoethnography as a research method which can be used to explore critical and personal issues among ELT teachers, discuss how duoethnography as a reflective practice can aid teachers in understanding themselves, their colleagues or their context, and demonstrate how duoethnography can be used as a pedagogical tool in ELT classrooms. The chapters are a range of duoethnographies from established and emerging researchers and teachers, which explore the interplay between cultural discourses and life histories with a focus on ELT in Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCulturally relevant pedagogy. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakers. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxResearchxMethodology. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingzJapan. 0aEthnologyxMethodology. 0aNarrative inquiry (Research method) 0aNarrative inquiry (Research method). 0aQualitative researchxMethodology. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  acritical applied linguistics.  aduoethnography.  apeer interaction.  aqualitative research.  areflective practice.  aresearch methodologies.1 aBrereton, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHooper, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c